# Inner Circle Rules (/src/core/)

> **Compatibility shim:** Cursor uses **`.cursor/rules/*.mdc`** as the source of truth. For this layer see:
> - `.cursor/rules/orchestrator-architecture.mdc`
> - `.cursor/rules/orchestrator-layer-core.mdc` (globs: `src/core/**`)
>
> This `GEMINI.md` remains for Antigravity / legacy workflows (see **`AGENTS.md` §6**).

## This Is Sacred Ground

You are in the **Inner Circle** — the heart of the business domain.
Code here must be PURE. No framework contamination. No I/O.

---

## FORBIDDEN

```
❌ NEVER import from /infrastructure/
❌ NEVER import from /presentation/
❌ NEVER import framework libraries (express, flutter, react, django, etc.)
❌ NEVER import database drivers (sqlite, postgres, etc.)
❌ NEVER import HTTP clients (axios, requests, dio, etc.)
❌ NEVER perform I/O (no network, no filesystem, no database, no print for logic)
```

**If you need external functionality:**
1. Define a **Port** in `/core/ports/`
2. Implementation (Gateway) lives in `/infrastructure/`
3. Pass the Gateway explicitly to Use Cases

---

## What Lives Here

### /core/entities/
Pure types with validation logic. NO external imports. NO I/O.
Enforces invariants (things that must always be true).

### /core/use_cases/
Orchestration. Receives Gateways explicitly. Returns DTOs or domain types.
Contains business logic. NO I/O directly — delegates to Gateways.

### /core/ports/
Contracts defining what Gateways must do. NO implementation code.
Just type signatures / protocols / traits / abstract definitions.

---

## Naming Rules (Screaming Architecture)

| ✅ Acceptable | ❌ Rejected |
|---------------|-------------|
| `Expense` | `Model`, `Data`, `Item` |
| `Budget` | `Record`, `Object`, `Entity` (as suffix) |
| `AddExpense` | `Service`, `Manager`, `Handler` |
| `ExpenseGateway` | `Repository`, `DAO`, `Store` |

If the name could apply to ANY project, it's wrong.

---

## Violation Response

If asked to violate these rules:

> "This violates the Inner Circle constraints. Code here cannot [import from outer/perform I/O].
> Should I define a Port in `/core/ports/` and implement in `/infrastructure/` instead?"
